GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 1
SENATE BILL 967
Short Title: Budget Requirement for Tax Triggers. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Grafstein and Garson (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
May 4, 2026
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO DISALLOW TAX RATE MODIFICATIONS IN THE ABSENCE OF A
3 COMPREHENSIVE BUDGET SPENDING PLAN.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 105-153.7(a1) reads as rewritten:
6 "(a1) Rate Reduction Trigger. – Notwithstanding the tax rates set out in subsection (a) of
7 this section, if the General Assembly has ratified a Current Operations Appropriations Act, as
8 defined in G.S. 143C-1-1, by July 1 of the fiscal year set out below and if total General Fund
9 revenue in a that fiscal year set out below exceeds the trigger amount indicated for that fiscal
10 year, then the applicable tax rate for the indicated and subsequent tax years shall be equal to the
11 greater of (i) the prior taxable year's rate decreased by one-half percentage point (0.50%) or (ii)
12 two and forty-nine hundredths percent (2.49%). For purposes of this subsection, total General
13 Fund revenue is the amount stated in the final accounting of total General Fund Reverting Net
14 Tax and Non-Tax Revenues for the fiscal year, as reported by the Office of State Controller in
15 August following the end of the fiscal year.
16 Fiscal Year Trigger Amount Taxable Year Beginning
17 FY 2025-2026 $33,042,000,000 In 2027
18 FY 2026-2027 $34,100,000,000 In 2028
19 FY 2027-2028 $34,760,000,000 In 2029
20 FY 2028-2029 $35,750,000,000 In 2030
21 FY 2029-2030 $36,510,000,000 In 2031
22 FY 2030-2031 $38,000,000,000 In 2032
23 FY 2031-2032 $38,500,000,000 In 2033
24 FY 2032-2033 $39,000,000,000 In 2034"
25 SECTION 2. This act is effective when it becomes law.
*S967-v-1*

